		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Heaven</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Heaven_(disambiguation)" title="Heaven (disambiguation)">Heaven (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Paradiso_Canto_31.jpg" class="image" title="Dante and Beatrice gaze upon the highest Heaven; from Gustave Doré's illustrations to the Divine Comedy."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Paradiso_Canto_31.jpg/300px-Paradiso_Canto_31.jpg" width="300" height="333" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Paradiso_Canto_31.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Dante_Alighieri" title="Dante Alighieri">Dante</a> and <a href="/wiki/Beatrice_Portinari" title="Beatrice Portinari">Beatrice</a> gaze upon the highest Heaven; from <a href="/wiki/Gustave_Dor%C3%A9" title="Gustave Doré">Gustave Doré</a>'s illustrations to the <i><a href="/wiki/Divine_Comedy" title="Divine Comedy">Divine Comedy</a></i>.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Heaven</b> may refer to the physical heavens, the <a href="/wiki/Atmosphere" title="Atmosphere">sky</a> or the seemingly endless expanse of the <a href="/wiki/Universe" title="Universe">universe</a> beyond. This is the traditional literal meaning of the term in English, however since at least AD 1000, it is typically also used to refer to an <a href="/wiki/Afterlife" title="Afterlife">afterlife</a> <a href="/wiki/Plane_of_existence" title="Plane of existence" class="mw-redirect">plane of existence</a> (often held to exist in another <a href="/wiki/Realm" title="Realm">realm</a>) in various <a href="/wiki/Religion" title="Religion">religions</a> and <a href="/wiki/Spirituality" title="Spirituality">spiritual</a> <a href="/wiki/Philosophy" title="Philosophy">philosophies</a>, often described as the <a href="/wiki/Sacred" title="Sacred">holiest</a> possible place, accessible by people according to various standards of <a href="/wiki/Divinity" title="Divinity">divinity</a>, <a href="/wiki/Good_and_evil" title="Good and evil">goodness</a>, <a href="/wiki/Piety" title="Piety">piety</a>, <a href="/wiki/Faith" title="Faith">faith</a> etc.</p>
